04771nam a22006015i 9781571137524DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815711375247 a10.1515/97815711375242doi  a(DE-B1597)675777  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a833.9209356qOCoLC222/ger/20230216  aGO 12110qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/43159:1 aYoungman, Paul A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWe Are the Machine :bThe Computer, the Internet, and Information in Contemporary German Literature /cPaul A. Youngman.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2009] 1bCamden House, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (187 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v4100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Machines, Computers, and the Liberal Humanist Subject -- t1: Losing Ground to the Machine: Electronic Brains in the Works of Heinrich Hauser and Friedrich Dürrenmatt -- t2: Fearing the Machine — Two Nightmares in the 1990s: Gerd Heidenreich’s New Riddle of the Sphinx and Barbara Frischmuth’s Hidden Meaning -- t3: Becoming the Machine: Günter Grass’s and Erich Loest’s Virtual History, René Pollesch’s Postdramatic Imaginings, and “Real” Cyber-Relationships according to Christine Eichel and Daniel Glattauer -- tConclusion: Questions to Ponder -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn investigation of attitudes toward -- and unease with -- Information Technology, as reflected in recent German-language literature.Despite our embrace of the sheer utility and productivity it has made possible, the revolution in Information Technology has led to unease about its possible misuse, abuse, and even its eventual domination of humankind. That German culture is not immune to this sense of disquiet is reflected in a broad variety of German-language fiction since the 1940s. This first study of the literary reception of IT in German-speaking lands begins with an analysis of a seminal novel from the beginning of the computer age, Heinrich Hauser's Gigant Hirn (1948), then moves to its primary focus, the literature of the past two decades, ranging from Gerd Heidenreich's Die Nacht der Händler (1995) to Daniel Glattauer's novel Gut gegen Nordwind (2006). Along the way, it analyzes eleven works, including Barbara Frischmuth's novel Die Schrift des Freundes (1998), René Pollesch's drama world wide web-slums (2001), and Günter Grass's novella Im Krebsgang (2003). As wildly different in approach as these works are, each has much to offer this investigation of the imaginary border dividing the human from the technological, a lingering, centuries-old construct created to ease the anxiety that technology has given rise to throughout the ages. Paul A. Youngman is Associate Professor of German at the University of North Carolina-Charlotteand Director of the Center for Humanities, Technology, and Science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComputers in literature. 0aGerman fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman fictionzEurope, German-speakingxHistory and criticism. 0aInformation technology in literature. 0aInternet in literature. 0aLiterature and technologyzGermany. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113752440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571137524423Coveruhttps: